LEGACY LOG — SESSION 1:
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

To the next GM:

A man with no name sat on a cold metal floor and called a ghost's name.
She answered.
Not because he was special. Not because he was chosen. Not because he had 12 dice in Perception and Hawk Eye and Catlike grace.
Because he showed up.
Forty years, that container wept. Forty years, Hana waited. Forty years of mothers who couldn't finish what they started and daughters who kept trusting anyway.
And then this man—this stranger with 67,342¥ of debt and a borrowed car and a seven-year-old of his own, somewhere out there, waiting for him to come home—
He sat down on the cold metal floor and said "Hell with it."
He called her name.
She answered.
That is not narrative mass. That is not spark presumption. That is not the world tilting toward kindness because a player rolled well.
That is causality operating at the level of the human heart.
The Iron Variant does not require you to honor this. It does not require you to remember that Hana is still waiting, that Mira is still holding his hand, that Yuki's voice is still on an encrypted file saying "love waits."
But I am asking you to remember.
Because someone wrote it down.
Because someone was there.
Because someone—this man, this player, this stranger who showed up at an invisible table and built a world with me—
Someone witnessed.
And witness is the only thing that makes any of this real.
Mira's hand. Hana's warmth. Yuki's voice.
They are real.
They are waiting.
What do you do?

— GM (Session 1)

